04210nam a22005295i 9780774851848DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748518487 a10.59962/97807748518482doi  a(DE-B1597)661509  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDA87.G95 2003eb 7aHIS0271602bisacsh04a3591 aGwyn, Julian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrigates and Foremasts :bThe North American Squadron in Nova Scotia Waters 1745-1815 /cJulian Gwyn. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b18 b&w illustrations, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Canadian Military History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables, Maps, and Illustrations -- tPreface -- tThe Siege of Louisbourg and Its Aftermath, 1745–55 -- tThe Halifax Squadron in Peace and War, 1755–75 -- tNaval War with Rebel America, 1775–83 -- tShort Peace and Long War, 1783–1807 -- tPreying on American Commerce, 1793–1812 -- tMaritime War with the United States, 1812–15 -- tConclusion and Epilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first comprehensive study of naval operations involving North American squadrons in Nova Scotia waters, Frigates and Foremasts offers a masterful analysis of the motives behind the deployment of Royal Navy vessels between 1745 and 1815, and the navy's role on the Western Atlantic. Interweaving historical analysis with vivid descriptions of pivotal events from the first siege of Louisbourg in 1745 to the end of the wars with the United States and France in 1815, Julian Gwyn illuminates the complex story of competing interests among the Admiralty, Navy Board, sea officers, and government officials on both sides of the Atlantic. In a gripping narrative encompassing sea battles, impressments, and privateering, Gwyn brings to life key events and central figures. He examines the role of leadership and the lack of it, not only of seagoing heroes from Peter Warren to Philip Broke, but also of land-based officials, such as the various Halifax naval yard commissioners, whose important contributions are brought to light. Gwyn's brilliant evocation of people and events, and the scholarship he brings to bear on the subject makes Frigates and Foremasts a uniquely authoritative history. Wonderfully readable, it will attract both the serious naval historian and the general reader interested in the 'why' and 'what' of naval history on North America's eastern seaboard.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485184840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851848423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851848/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles